═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  data/tls/ — Production Certificates (Runtime)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  This is where PRODUCTION certificates go. The unikernel reads
  these at boot from /data/tls/ via VirtioFS — no rebuild needed.

  Not to be confused with certs/ which holds the embedded dev
  fallback certificate compiled into the binary. See certs/README.

  Place your TLS certificate and private key here:

    data/tls/cert.pem   ← Full certificate chain (PEM format)
    data/tls/key.pem    ← Private key (PEM format, unencrypted)

  The unikernel loads these from /data/tls/ at boot via VirtioFS.
  If no files are found, it falls back to the embedded dev certificate.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  CLOUDFLARE ORIGIN CERTIFICATE (Recommended for production)
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  1. Log in to Cloudflare Dashboard → your domain → SSL/TLS
  2. Go to "Origin Server" tab
  3. Click "Create Certificate"
     - Private key type: ECDSA (recommended) or RSA
     - Hostnames: your domain (e.g., *.example.com, example.com)
     - Validity: 15 years (default)
  4. Copy the Origin Certificate → save as  data/tls/cert.pem
  5. Copy the Private Key       → save as  data/tls/key.pem
  6. Set Cloudflare SSL mode to "Full (Strict)"

  The unikernel picks up the certs on next boot — no rebuild needed.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  SELF-SIGNED CERTIFICATE (For development/testing)
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Generate a self-signed cert with the included script:

    ./scripts/gen-cert.sh data/tls

  This creates cert.pem and key.pem in this directory.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  VIRTIOFS DEPLOYMENT
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  When running with VirtioFS, sync this directory to the shared
  filesystem so the guest can read it at /data/tls/:

    cp data/tls/cert.pem /tmp/guestfs/data/tls/cert.pem
    cp data/tls/key.pem  /tmp/guestfs/data/tls/key.pem

  For remote/production servers using KVM + VirtioFS, place the
  certs in whatever directory is shared as /data/ on the guest.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  SECURITY NOTES
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  - NEVER commit real certificates or private keys to git.
  - The actual .pem files in this directory are gitignored.
  - Only this README is tracked in version control.
  - Keep private keys with restricted permissions (chmod 600).

